postcontent: This one has been stored in a gun safe in a climate controlled home.  It's a 7.62 x 51mm LWRCI REPR, meaning it also takes 308 Winchester rounds. And REPR stands for Rapid Engagement Precision Rifle. 20 inch barrel, the desireable 10 twist, best gas piston system in the industry, highly desireable left side charging handle so you don't break your cheek-weld (just reach up with left hand to grab it), billet aluminum construction for quality, and ATLAS Bipod ($300 bipod) attached, and factory back up iron sights.  This rifle is known for MOA and sub MOA accuracy to 1,000 yards. Shotgun news did a write up on this rifle and they got 0.3 MOA groups at 100 yds with Federal's Gold Medal Match 168 gr Sierra Matchkings.  Rifle has only had 50-60 rounds fired through it. I love the gun but I am selling it because I am moving out of state soon and want the money to go towards earnest money for a home build.  This particular model of REPR is sought after because the barrel is non-fluted and they are known for extreme accuracy. The non-fluted barrel won't warp, compared to what you risk with the newer model with a spiral fluted barrel. They should have put a straight flute on the barrel if any kind of fluting at all was to be used, but they spiral fluted it and that is not wise to have under a sustained fire or shooting in hot weather. Rifle was $3975 new. Atlas bipod was $300 with two sets of prongs to fit on it. One regular and one pair of spiked prongs which are for sand or soft ground. That's $4275.  I am selling it for $3600. title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 146b .22LR
postcontent: One of the last pieces of my vintage .22 collection and I daresay, one of the best. This is a 1940's vintage Mossberg, from when rifles were made to last. This is a full size, tube fed bolt action. It has the T bolt handle that still shows some faded case colors. The bluing is excellent and original. No big scratches or anything of the sort. It is complete with all the original sights, including the usually missing S-130 peep sight and interchangeable flip up front sight (the model number escapes me at the moment). The stock is in near perfect shape, original finish. The only thing worth mentioning condition-wise on the entire rifle is some minor shrinkage in the molded trigger guard. You wouldn't notice unless you were looking for it. It's minor enough that I never bothered refitting it. Unfortunately I do not have sling swivels for it. I never bothered much with slings. This is kind of a rare bird as it will shoot short and long rifle .22 ammo.This is one of my last pieces because although it's a sporting gun, it is flat out the best shooting .22 I've owned- and I've owned many. Shot it side by side against my Winchester 52 and 75, Remington 512T and various other target guns and spanked them all. It loves Remington Auto Match and Wolf MT. Challenge the kid in the next lane with the tricked out 10-22 and win some beers.If you've been wanting one of these, now's your rare chance at a near pristine example. You won't find one nicer.
